tools.migration.tip.SpecifyUpdateDetails.location: Indicates the installation path of the new TIBCO MDM version. The new MQ_HOME location is automatically detected.
tools.migration.tip.SpecifyUpdateDetails.version: Indicates the release version that you want to migrate to. By default, the current version is selected. If you want to change the version, select another version from the drop-down list.
tools.migration.tip.SpecifyUpdateDetails.GDSNEnabled: By default, {No} is selected. If you have installed the GDSN plug-in, {Yes} is selected. The options are read-only.
tools.migration.tip.SpecifyUpdateDetails.preLocation: All the previous MDM installations are detected and displayed under TIBCO_HOME. You can change the value, if required. Click {Browse} to select another location.
tools.migration.tip.SpecifyUpdateDetails.preVersion: Refers to the version you are migrating from. The version options are displayed in a drop-down list.
tools.migration.tip.SpecifyUpdateDetails.preGDSNEnable: Select {Yes} if the previous version was GDSN enabled. For GDSN Edition, first you have to migrate MDM to MDM, install the GDSN latest version, and then run Add-on Plug-in Installer. Copy the Plug-in directory from the previous MQ_HOME to  the new MQ_HOME directory.
tools.migration.tip.IdentifyLocation.newDirPath: Specify the MQ_COMMON_DIR path of the currently installed TIBCO MDM version. For example, G:\MDM_Installation\mdm\8.3\common
tools.migration.tip.IdentifyLocation.newXmlPath: Specify the location of ConfigValues.xml file for the currently installed TIBCO MDM version. For example, G:\MDM_Installation\mdm\8.3\common\config
tools.migration.tip.IdentifyLocation.ExistingDirPath: Refer to the path of the previous MQ_COMMON_DIR directory. This value is automatically retrieved from the MQ_COMMON_DIR environment variable.
tools.migration.tip.IdentifyLocation.ExistingXmlPath: Refer to the path of the previous ConfigValues.xml file directory location. This value is automatically retrieved from the MQ_CONFIG environment variable.
tools.migration.tip.DefineDBMigration.DBHost: Specify the database host name or IP address.
tools.migration.tip.DefineDBMigration.userName: Specify the username for the database.
tools.migration.tip.DefineDBMigration.password: Specify the password for the database
tools.migration.tip.DefineDBMigration.serverName: Specify the name of the SQL Server. For example, localhost, IP address, or myhost\MDM. If you have selected the SQL Server database type, the Server Name field is enabled.

tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.QueueDefinition.LogicalName: Specify the logical queue name to send received messages to the application. For example, MyIntegrationInboundIntgrMsg.  The logical queue name is mapped to the physical queue name.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.QueueDefinition.PhysicalName: Specify the physical queue name. For example, Q_CIM_CUSTOMIZATION_SAMPLE_INBOUND_INTGR_MSG.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.QueueDefinition.WebsphereInfo: Specify extension attributes for a queue.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.CommunicationContext.name: The communication context name is automatically generated. It is based on the logical queue name. You can edit the communication context name. For example, JMSMYIntegrationInboundIntgrMsg. However, it is recommended to use the system-generated name whenever possible.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.CommunicationContext.property: These properties are added to the inbound message when received in the previously specified communication context.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.ReceiverManager.name: The receiver manager name is automatically generated using the logical queue name. You can edit the receiver manager name. For example, MYIntegrationInboundIntgrMsgInboundQueueReceiverManager. It is recommended to use the system-generated name whenever possible.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.ReceiverManager.class: Select the Receiver manager class. The available options are MqMessageReceiverManager or MqDynamicallyFilteredMessageReceiverManager. It is recommended to use the system-generated name whenever possible unless you want to define selectors for some messages.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.ReceiverManager.poolSize: Determines how many messages from the new queue can be processed in parallel. The default value is {eight}.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.ReceiverManager.mode: Determines how the acknowledgement of the processed message is generated. The default value is {autoAck} (automatic acknowledgement). The other options are {clientAck} (explicit client-based acknowledgement) and {dupsOKAck} (duplicate messages are acceptable).
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.ReceiverManager.ioTemplate: Select any one of the following IO process templates: {StandardInboundIntgrMsgByteStreamMsgIOProcess}, {StandardInboundIntgrMsgStringMsgIOProcess}, {InboundIntgrMsgIOProcess}, {StandardInboundIntgrMsgUTFStringMsgIOProcess}, {StandardIntgrEventByteStreamMsgIOProcess}, {StandardIntgrEventStringMsgIOProcess}, and {StandardIntgrEventUTFStringMsgIOProcess}. For information on these templates, refer to the Queue Management chapter in TIBCO MDM System Administration.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.Unmarshalers.messageProcessor: If you have selected an IO process template in the Receiver Manager step, some message processors are preselected and ordered in a particular sequence. Select the message processors to use in the pipeline by selecting the corresponding check box. Using the arrow keys, you can order the sequence in which the processors are to be used in the pipeline for message extraction.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.Unmarshalers.messageContentExtractor: For the Message content extractor, you can either select processors from the drop-down list or enter your own message processor name. The {Edit} link enables you to edit the  properties for user-defined processors.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.Unmarshalers.messageContentPeocessor: Select the message content extractor from the drop-down list. The {Edit} link enables you to edit the properties for user-defined processors.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.SenderManager.name: The sender manager name is automatically generated using the logical queue name. You can edit the name. For example, MYIntegrationInboundIntgrMsgInboundQueueSenderManager.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.SenderManager.class: Select the sender manager class. The available options are MqMessageSenderManager or MqDynamicallyFilteredMessageSenderManager. It is recommended  to use the system-generated name whenever possible, unless you want to define the selectors for some messages.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.SenderManager.poolSize: Determines how many messages from the new queue can be processed in parallel. The default value is {eight}.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.Marshalers.messageProcessor: Message content processors processes the content and convert it to desired packaging.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.Marshalers.messageCreator: The message creator extracts payload (content) from received message so that the content can be processed by other marsheler.
tools.defineNewQueue.inbound.tip.Marshalers.messageFormatter: The message formatters allow processing of the message before sending it out. The message formatters are typically used to do any booking tasks.
